bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Neufmarche was born in 1150, in Shropshire, England, her father, De Neufmarche, was 26 and her mother, De Neufmarche, was 25. She had at least 1 son with Ralph II le Boteler. She died in 1210, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1150–1210":"1150–1210","1125–1207":"1125–1207","1162–1226":"1162–1226","1185–1246":"1185–1246","1174–1244":"1174–1244","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1126–Female":"1126–Surnud","1226":"1226","1126":"1126","1246":"1246","1125":"1125","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","1185":"1185","1174":"1174","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1207":"1207","Wemme, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Oversley, Warwickshire, England":"Oversley Green, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1150–1210":"1150–1210","1125–1207":"1125–1207","1162–1226":"1162–1226","1185–1246":"1185–1246","1174–1244":"1174–1244","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1126–Female":"1126–Kuollut","1226":"1226","1126":"1126","1246":"1246","1125":"1125","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","1185":"1185","1174":"1174","1162":"1162","1150":"1150","1207":"1207","Wemme, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England",